{
  "texts": [
    "Let Assumption 1 hold.",
    "The dual function is strictly convex and smooth with parameter L D, i.e., 0 ≺ ∇ 2 D(λ) ⪯ L D I.",
    "Moreover, if the smallest singular value of Hessian is strictly positive for some λ, i.e., µ D (λ):= σ min (∇ 2 D(λ)) > 0, then the dual function is strongly convex with parameter µ D in an ϵ D -neighborhood of λ, i.e., µ D I ⪯ ∇ 2 D(λ ′) for any λ ′ that satisfies ∥λ ′ -λ∥ ≤ ϵ D.We defer the proof of Lemma 1 to Appendix A.1.",
    "Due to the smoothness and local strong convexity, we can apply gradient-based methods to find the optimal dual variable λ ⋆, provided that the gradient of the dual function is estimated efficiently, e.g., the plug-in estimator [21,Appendix E].",
    "Given an optimal dual variable λ ⋆, recovery of the optimal policy π ⋆ can be achieved via the strong duality."
  ]
}